article.description:
Keith Langford had 23 points to lead four
Kansas players with at least 20 and the 14th-ranked Jayhawks
rebounded from their embarrassing Thanksgiving week with a 97-70
victory over Central Missouri State on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Langford leads Jayhawks with 23 points
article.linkText: Langford, Kansas end losing streak in rout of Mules
article.story:
LAWRENCE, Kan. -- Wayne Simien didn't play like he had a
sore right ankle.

	   The sophomore forward scored a career-high 22 points -- one of
four Kansas players with at least 20 -- and grabbed 10 rebounds as
the (No. 13 ESPN/USA Today, No. 14 AP) Jayhawks rebounded from their embarrassing
Thanksgiving week with a 97-70 victory over Central Missouri State
on Wednesday night.

	   "It's going to bother me. That's just what it's going to do,''
said Simien, whose only concession to the lingering injury was to
stand when he wasn't in the game to keep the joint from stiffening.
"I'm just trying to do what the doctors tell me to do, and trying
to stay healthy. It's something that will probably stay with me for
a little while.''

	   Simien scored 10 points on dunks and finished 10-for-11 from the
field in 26 minutes.

	   "I was hoping to keep his minutes down,'' coach Roy Williams
said. "I didn't want the ankle bothering him. It's something we're
trying to be very guarded about.''

	   Keith Langford's 23 points led the Jayhawks (3-2), who were
coming off losses in the Preseason NIT to North Carolina and
Florida. Nick Collison had 22 points, and sophomore point guard
Aaron Miles added a career-high 20 points and had seven assists.

	   Miles sounded more concerned about his four turnovers, though.

	   "I still think I am turning the ball over too much,'' he said.
"There are a lot of aspects I can improve on.''

	   Kansas didn't take its first 20-point lead over the Mules (4-1)
until Langford's layup with 8:46 remaining made it 78-58.

	   The Jayhawks got their first field goal from a reserve 15
seconds later when Michael Lee's driving layup game them a 22-point
lead.

	   Kansas dominated inside, outscoring the smaller Mules -- an NCAA
Division II team -- 46-22 in the paint, outrebounding them 52-21 and
blocking 10 shots. Collison had five blocks, one short of his
career high.

	   "They're 6-foot-9 and above, and we're 6-foot-5 and below,''
said Central Missouri State forward Brian Rhodes -- who is 6-6,
according to the Mules' media guide, but is still three inches
shorter than Simien. "It's tough. In our league, there are not
many guys that far up there.''

	   The Jayhawks' perimeter defense was less dominating, though,
allowing Central Missouri State to make 10 3-pointers and keep the
game close into the second half.

	   "That all goes to giving up penetration,'' Langford said.
"Somebody hits a 3-pointer with a hand in his face, that's one
thing -- but we were giving up too many penetrations and letting
them kick the ball back out to the open man.''

	   Vince Haynes hit three 3-pointers and led Central Missouri State
with 17 points. Jeremy McFall, who also hit three 3s, added 15
points and James Collins and Rhodes each had 10.

	   The Mules, who missed their first five shots and trailed 8-0
less than 2 minutes into the game, scored their first 18 points on
6-for-12 shooting from 3-point range. They didn't make a 2-point
basket until McFall hit a jumper from just inside the line with
10:32 left in the half to cut Kansas' lead to 25-22.

	   Kansas responded with a 13-3 run over the next five minutes for
a 38-25 lead and led 49-36 at halftime. The Mules got within double
digits once in the second half, when Mark DeBaun's basket cut the
margin to 59-50 with 15:39 remaining, but Kansas answered with a
13-5 run over the next 4 minutes.

	   The Jayhawks were without senior guard Kirk Hinrich. The
preseason All-American has a strained back but is expected to play
on Saturday against No. 7 Oregon.

	   That game is a rematch of last year's NCAA Midwest Regional
final, won 104-86 by Kansas.
	   
Hinrich's replacement on Wednesday, junior Bryant Nash, had two
points and eight rebounds.
